    {
      "id": "4609dac1-59ba-4fb5-a64c-f6e7776f2879",
      "timestamp": "2026-06-22T17:57:35.286024+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "All done. Here's a summary of the changes:\n\n## What was done\n\n### New method on `StyleManager`\n\nAdded `scaled_tab_width(multiplier=1.0) -> int` which computes `math.ceil(nice_tab_width() * zoom_factor * multiplier)`. This centralises the zoom-scaled tab width calculation and always rounds **up** to the nearest pixel, ensuring the content fills the available column width at every zoom level.\n\n### 10 files updated to use the new method\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `style_manager.py` | Added `import math` + new `scaled_tab_width()` method |\n| `conversation_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` now call `scaled_tab_width()` |\n| `conversation_widget.py` | `_update_input_width()` now calls `scaled_tab_width()` |\n| `editor_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` |\n| `preview_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` |\n| `shell_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` |\n| `log_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` |\n| `usage_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` and `setMaximumWidth()` (uses `self._style_manager.` prefix) |\n| `diff_tab.py` | `preferred_width()` now calls `scaled_tab_width(2.0)` for side-by-side |\n| `tab_manager.py` | Default column width uses `scaled_tab_width()`; proportional downscale path uses `math.ceil()` instead of `int()` |\n\n### The key behavioural change\n\nBefore: `int(1024.0 * 1.15)` = `int(1177.6)` = **1177** \u2014 lost ~1px per column.\n\nAfter: `math.ceil(1024.0 * 1.15)` = **1178** \u2014 uses full available width.\n\nThis affects both the column sizing in `show_all_columns()` *and* the inner content widget caps via `setMaximumWidth()`, so the fix is consistent at both levels.\n\nAll three static analysis checks (dependency checker, mypy, pylint) pass cleanly.",
      "completed": true,
