      "content": "The changes are correctly applied. Let me think about what's different...\n\nWait. Let me re-read the `apply_style` ordering for the usage tab carefully:\n\n```python\ndef apply_style(self) -> None:\n    self._usage_widget.apply_style()        # \u2190 calls refresh \u2192 emits refreshed\n    self._usage_widget.setMaximumWidth(...)  # \u2190 runs AFTER refresh\n```\n\nAnd `apply_style` in `UsageWidget`:\n```python\ndef apply_style(self) -> None:\n    ...\n    self.refreshed.emit()\n```\n\nAnd `_on_widget_refreshed`:\n```python\ndef _on_widget_refreshed(self) -> None:\n    new_stylesheet = self._build_stylesheet()\n    if new_stylesheet != self.styleSheet():\n        self.setStyleSheet(new_stylesheet)\n```\n\nSo when `apply_style` is called:\n1. `_usage_widget.apply_style()` \u2192 emits `refreshed` \u2192 `_on_widget_refreshed` \u2192 `setStyleSheet()` \n2. `_usage_widget.setMaximumWidth(...)` \u2192 runs after\n\nSetting a stylesheet after setting max width can reset widget properties in Qt. But `setMaximumWidth` comes after, so that's actually the right order.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user said \"some zoom levels not using the full width.\" The key phrase is \"some zoom levels.\" So at certain zoom levels it works, at others it doesn't. This is consistent with the rounding issue \u2014 but we fixed it. Unless...\n\nThe issue might be that the `setMaximumWidth` and the `preferred_width` return the **same** value, but the column sizing in `show_all_columns` gives the column exactly that width (since `total_preferred <= available`), and then the splitter handle takes 1px, leaving the content with 1px less than its max width. The spacers then absorb the difference:\n\n```python\nmargin = (available - total_preferred) // 2\n```\n\nIf `available - total_preferred` is odd, one pixel is lost to integer division. But this would affect ALL tabs equally, not just preview and usage.\n\nLet me look at the problem from the perspective of the actual widgets. Let me compare what `_preview_content_widget` and `_usage_widget` are vs `_shell_widget` and `_log_widget`. Maybe preview and usage widgets have internal scroll areas that set their own line wrap width based on viewport, and the viewport width calculation is separate:",
