      "content": "The `apply_style` method calls `self.refreshed.emit()` but NOT `self.refresh()`. The refresh is only called when `usage_updated` or `language_changed` fires, or during init. So during a zoom change, the content isn't rebuilt \u2014 just the margins and stylesheet are updated.\n\nLet me look at this from a completely different angle. The user said \"that's working for conversations, humbug shell and mindspace log.\" These three are the tabs that were most recently updated with the container/HBox pattern. Maybe preview and usage were updated separately and have a subtly different container setup.\n\nActually \u2014 wait. Let me look at whether the `setStyleSheet` call in `_build_stylesheet` or `_on_widget_refreshed` might be resetting the `maximumWidth`. In Qt, setting a stylesheet with `setStyleSheet()` can indeed reset certain widget properties. Specifically, if the stylesheet is applied to the tab widget itself, it can affect child widgets.\n\nLet me look more carefully at what object the stylesheet is set on. In the preview tab:\n- `_build_stylesheet` returns CSS targeting `#PreviewWidget QWidget`\n- This is set on `self` (the PreviewTab)\n- The `_preview_content_widget` has object name \"PreviewWidget\"\n\nSo the stylesheet `#PreviewWidget QWidget { background-color: ... }` is set on the PreviewTab, but targets widgets inside the PreviewWidget. This shouldn't affect maximum width.\n\nI'm now going to take a step back and consider that maybe the problem is **not about max width at all**, but about the **column sizing itself**. Let me think about what happens when there are multiple tabs in a column. `show_all_columns` takes the **max** preferred width across all tabs in the column. If a preview or usage tab is in a column with another tab that has a different preferred width, the column could be wider or narrower than expected, and the content widget's max width would cap it.\n\nBut the user said the issue affects preview and usage tabs, implying