      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Identical pattern.\n\nI've exhausted my code analysis. The code is structurally identical across all tab types. Let me ask the user for more specifics, since I can't reproduce the visual issue from code alone.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider one thing. The preview and usage tabs may not have been open when the user tested. Or... let me re-read the user's message: \"ok that's working for conversations, humbug shell and mindspace log but not preview tabs or usage tabs\"\n\nCould it be that the **application hasn't been rebuilt/restarted** and these tabs were created with old code? No, the user is testing after our changes...\n\nLet me look at one more thing. The usage tab has the order reversed in `apply_style`:\n\n```python\n# Usage:\nself._usage_widget.apply_style()         # \u2190 calls refreshed.emit() \u2192 setStyleSheet\nself._usage_widget.setMaximumWidth(...)  # \u2190 AFTER\n```\n\nvs all others:\n```python\n# Others:\nself._X_widget.setMaximumWidth(...)      # \u2190 FIRST\nself._X_widget.apply_style()             # \u2190 SECOND\n```\n\nFor usage, when `apply_style` is called:\n1. `self._usage_widget.apply_style()` emits `refreshed`\n2. This triggers `_on_widget_refreshed()` which calls `self._build_stylesheet()` and `self.setStyleSheet(new_stylesheet)`\n3. **Setting a stylesheet on the tab widget can reset layout properties of child widgets**\n4. Then `setMaximumWidth` is called, which should fix the max width\n\nBut wait \u2014 what if `_on_widget_refreshed`'s `setStyleSheet` call triggers a layout invalidation that happens asynchronously (Qt events), and then `setMaximumWidth` is called synchronously, but the stylesheet hasn't fully propagated yet? This is a stretch.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be a simpler explanation. Let me look at the usage tab's `apply_style` more carefully. The usage widget's `apply_style` emits `refreshed`, which is connected to `_on_widget_refreshed`. But `_on_widget_refreshed` only sets the stylesheet \u2014 it does NOT call `setMaximumWidth`. So when the usage widget's content is refreshed (e.g., from a usage_updated signal), the max width is NOT re-applied.\n\nBut that's the content refresh, not the zoom change. On zoom change, `apply_style` is called which does set the max width.\n\nOK, I think I need to just ask the user. But let me check one final thing \u2014 maybe the preview and usage tabs have an issue where the **container widget** (the one with the HBox layout) is the one that should have the max width, not the content widget:",
