      "content": "Nothing that resets width. \n\nOK here's one last idea. Let me check the `show_all_columns` method more carefully. The `QSplitter.setSizes()` call might not be giving the column the exact requested width. Let me check if maybe there's a `minimumSize` or `maximumSize` on the column widget or content widget that's interfering:\n\nActually, wait. I just realized something. When I look at the `show_all_columns` code:\n\n```python\ntotal_preferred += self._column_splitter.handleWidth() * (len(self._tab_columns) - 1)\n\nif total_preferred <= available:\n    for i, p in enumerate(col_preferred):\n        sizes[i] = max(min_col_width, p)\n    margin = (available - total_preferred) // 2\n```\n\nThe `total_preferred` includes the splitter handle widths. So each column gets its preferred width, plus handle widths between them. The remaining space goes to spacers.\n\nBut `setSizes` on QSplitter treats the sizes as **suggested** sizes and redistributes them to fill the splitter's total width. So if `available` is 2000 and we have one column with preferred 1178, the splitter will set the column to 1178 and... well, there are also left/right spacers as separate widgets in the splitter, so the total should work out.\n\nWait, are the spacers part of the splitter? Let me check:",
