      "timestamp": "2026-06-22T18:18:21.838766+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "All checks pass. Here's what was happening:\n\nThe old code computed both spacers with `// 2`:\n\n```python\nmargin = (available - total_preferred) // 2\nself._left_spacer.setFixedWidth(margin)\nself._right_spacer.setFixedWidth(margin)\n```\n\nWhen the slack (`available - total_preferred`) was **odd**, the two spacers together consumed `2 * (slack // 2)`, leaving 1 pixel unaccounted for. That extra pixel went into the splitter, making the column 1px wider than `scaled_tab_width()`. The content widget's `setMaximumWidth` then capped it, producing the visible 1px gap \u2014 but only at zoom levels where the arithmetic worked out to an odd slack value.\n\nThe fix gives the leftover pixel to the left spacer:\n\n```python\nslack = available - total_preferred\nself._left_spacer.setFixedWidth(math.ceil(slack / 2))\nself._right_spacer.setFixedWidth(slack // 2)\n```\n\nNow the two spacers always consume exactly `slack` pixels, so the splitter gets exactly `total_preferred` and the column width matches the content widget's max width precisely.",
